{"badges":["TM5","TM6"],"preparations":[{"content":["Grease a large bowl and baking tray then set aside. Place butter, milk, yeast and sugar in mixing bowl then heat <nobr>3 min\/37°C\/speed 2<\/nobr>.","Add flour, salt and 1 egg and mix <nobr>20 sec\/speed 4<\/nobr>, then knead <nobr>4 min\/<\/nobr>. Tip out into greased bowl, cover with cling film and leave to rise until doubled in size (approx. 2 hours).","Tip dough out onto a lightly floured surface then knock back dough. Divide into twelve equal sized pieces and roll each piece into a rope 35-40 cm long.","Take two pieces and twist them around each other, pinch ends together, then bring together into a circle. Repeat with the remaining pieces of dough until you have six portions. Place on greased baking tray and leave to rise again until doubled in size (approx. 1 hour). Meanwhile prepare eggs.","Using a paintbrush, brush different food colouring pastes over the 8 remaining eggs then set aside to dry.","Preheat oven to 180°C. Brush twisted dough with beaten egg yolk then sprinkle with pearl sugar. In the middle of each ring, gently place a dyed egg. Bake for 20 minutes (180°C) until golden. Transfer to a wire rack to cool before serving."]}],"ingredients":[{"title":"","content":["40 g butter, plus extra for greasing","215 g milk","1 ½ tsp dried instant yeast","105 g sugar","450 g strong white bread flour, plus extra for dusting","½ tsp fine sea salt","9 medium eggs","food colouring pastes, for dying eggs","1 egg yolk, for glaze","10 g pearl sugar"]}],"id":"r87636","imageLink":"https:\/\/1.bp.blogspot.com\/-11LAnBUrTSg\/XZaonCrGjII\/AAAAAAAAhL0\/P7eWoDN5okoKGVWQqabuagYIDH69A8FBQCLcBGAsYHQ\/s1600\/0_tWSc0SMtwcd7HpWM.png","title":"Italian Easter Bread","publishedAt":"2016-02-29T00:00:00Z","nutrition":{"protein":"20.4 g","fat":"15.8 g","uom":"per 1 pieces","carbohydrates":"69.8 g","calories":"2104 kJ \/ 503 kcal"},"usefulItems":"baking tray, large bowl, cling film, paint brush, cooling rack, pastry brush, oven","hintsAndTricks":["The egg will hard-boil in the oven, so you can peel and eat that too! As with any hard-boiled eggs, however, it would need to be consumed fairly soon after cooking or refrigerated for later.","A traditional Italian Easter recipe, the sweetened bread dough is shaped into a wreath and then dyed eggs are laid on to it before baking. Easter is a celebration of rebirth and hope and the eggs are used as a symbolic representation of their association with fertility and rebirth."],"basicInfo":["medium","30m","3h 50m","6 pieces"]}